t , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"\"Hên\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Jennifer  , occasionally used independently."],"variants":[{"name":"Jennifer","meanings":["Of Celtic (Arthurian) origin, a Cornish form of the name of King Arthur's unfaithful   Guinevere .  At the beginning of the 20th century, the name was merely a Cornish curiosity, but since then it has become enormously popular all over the English-speaking world, partly due to the influence of the film star  Jennifer Jones  (  1919–2009 , born as  Phyllis Isley ). Another factor in its rise was probably  Bernard Shaw's  use of it for the character of Jennifer Dubedat in The Doctor's Dilemma (  1905 ).  See also  Gaynor .  More recent well-known bearers include the American tennis player  Jennifer Capriati  (  b. 1976 ) and the British comedienne  Jennifer Saunders  (  b. 1958 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maelgwn \"Ieuanc\" ap Maelgwn \"Hên\" was born about 1170, in Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Maelgwn \"Hên\", was 25 and his mother, Mrs Maelgwn \"Hên\", was 27. He had at least 2 daughters. He died in 1257, at the age of 88."},"et":{"about 1170–1257":"umbes 1170–1257","1170–1257":"1170–1257","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1147–Male":"1147–Surnud","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1257":"1257","1147":"1147","1145":"1145","1200":"1200","1170":"1170","of Ceredigion gwlad, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1170–1257":"noin 1170–1257","1170–1257":"1170–1257","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","1147–Male":"1147–Kuollut","1145–Female":"1145–Kuollut","about 1170":"noin 1170","1257":"1257","1147":"1147","1145":"1145","1200":"1200","1170":"1170","of Ceredigion gwlad, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1170–1257":"environ 1170–1257","1170–1257":"1170–1257","1200–Female":"1200–Décédée","1147–Male":"1147–Décédé","1145–Female":"1145–Décédée","about 1170":"environ 1170","1257":"1257","1147":"1147","1145":"1145","1200":"1200","1170":"1170","of Ceredigion gwlad, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Maelgwn \"Ieuanc\" ap Maelgwn \"Hên\" est né environ 1170, à Cardiganshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni, son père, Maelgwn \"Hên\", avait 25 ans et sa mère, Mrs Maelgwn \"Hên\", avait 27 ans. Il a eu au moins 2 filles. Il est décédé en 1257, à l’âge de 88 ans."},"de":{"about 1170–1257":"um 1170–1257","1170–1257":"1170–1257","1200–Female":"1200–Verstorben","1147–Male":"1147–Verstorben","1145–Female":"1145–Verstorben","about 11